 at what price. He explores the (mis)representation of Zweig's rescue in East Germany and what this reveals about that country's understanding of its Nazi past. Finally he looks at the telling of the Zweig rescue story since German unification: a story told in the GDR to praise communists has become a story used to condemn them. Bill Niven is Professor of Contemporary German History at the Nottingham Trent University, UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-fascist movementszGermany (East). 0aCollective memoryzGermany (East). 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campsxLiberationzGermanyzWeimar (Thuringia). 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aBuchenwald Concentration Camp.  aCommunist Prisoners.  aEast Germany.  aGerman Democratic Republic.  aJewish Child.  aNazi Past.  aNazi Resistance.  aPropaganda.  aStefan Zweig.  aUprising.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781571136947?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571136947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571136947/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles